==Hebrew==

===Etymology===
Apparently from {{m|he|יָד||hand|sc=Hebr|tr=yad}}; literally, perhaps conveying the notion of being [[hand in hand]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Modern Israeli}} {{IPA|he|/jaˈdid/}}

===Noun===
{{he-noun|wv=יָדִיד|tr=yadíd|g=m|cons=יְדִיד|pl=יְדִידִים|plcons=יְדִידֵי|f=יְדִידָה|pat=קָטִיל}}

# A (male) platonic [[friend]].

====Usage notes====
* While the synonym {{m|he|חָבֵר|tr=khavér}} is more common in Modern Hebrew, it is ambiguous between a platonic friend and a romantic one; {{m|he|יָדִיד}} may therefore be used to avoid this ambiguity, though the question {{l|he||חבר חבר או רק חבר?|tr=khaver khaver o rak khaver?|gloss=boyfriend-friend or just friend?}} is also used.

